Netflix Data Analysis - Trends, Insights & Visualizations

Project Overview

This project focuses on analyzing Netflixs title dataset to uncover patterns in content types, genres, durations, country contributions, and trends over the years. The goal is to turn raw data into actionable insights through data cleaning, visualization, and exploration.

Dataset Overview

Source - Netflix Movies and TV Shows dataset

Columns - Title, Director, Cast, Country, Release Year, Rating, Duration, Genres, etc.

Missing Values - Some columns (like Director, Cast, Country) contain missing values.

from collections import Counter 

country_list = df['country'].dropna().apply(lambda x: x.split(', '))
all_countries = [country for sublist in country_list for country in sublist]
country_count = Counter(all_countries)

country_df = pd.DataFrame(country_count.items(), columns = ['country','count'])
country_df = country_df.sort_values(by = 'count', ascending = False).head(10)

Genre Analysis -

Top genres: International Movies, Dramas, Comedies

Created barplots and word clouds to visualize genre frequency

In [33]:
from collections import Counter 

#spliting each row into a list of genres 
genre_list = df['listed_in'].dropna().apply(lambda x: [genre.strip() for genre in x.split (',')])

#flatten the list 
all_genres = [genre for sublist in genre_list for genre in sublist]

#count how often genre appears
genre_count = Counter(all_genres)

#converting to dataframe 
genre_df = pd.DataFrame(genre_count.items(), columns =['genre','count'])

genre_df = genre_df.sort_values(by='count',ascending = False,).head(10).reset_index(drop=True)

movies = df [ df['type'] == 'Movie'].copy()
tv_shows = df [ df['type'] == 'TV Show' ].copy()

#For movies - extract the number of minutes
movies['duration_int'] = movies['duration'].str.extract('(\d+)').astype(float)

#for tv shows - extract number of seasons
tv_shows['duration_int'] = tv_shows['duration'].str.extract('(\d+)').astype(float)

#movie data
movie_countries = movies[['country','duration_int']].dropna()

#split multiple countries 
movie_countries = movie_countries.assign(country=movie_countries['country'].str.split(', '))

#explode so that each row has one county
movie_countries = movie_countries.explode('country')
In [38]:
#Group and average duration per country
avg_duration_by_country = movie_countries.groupby('country')['duration_int'].mean().sort_values(ascending = False).head(10)

#covert dataframe from plotting
avg_duration_df = avg_duration_by_country.reset_index()

from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS

text=" ".join(df['description'].dropna())

stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)

wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 1000, height = 500, background_color='black', stopwords = stopwords, colormap='Set2', random_state=42).generate(text)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation ='bilinear')
plt.axis('off')
plt.title("Most Common Words in Netflix Description", fontsize=16)
plt.show()

In [59]:
df['date_added'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date_added'])
df['year_added'] = df['date_added'].dt.year
df['month_added'] = df['date_added'].dt.month_name()

#grouping by year and month and count content added 

monthly_trends = df.groupby(['year_added','month_added']).size().reset_index(name='count')

#To plot months in calendar order, define category with month names ordered

months_order = ["January", "February", "March", "April", "May", "June", "July", "August", "September", "October", "November", "December"]

monthly_trends['month_added'] = pd.Categorical(monthly_trends['month_added'], categories = months_order, ordered = True)

monthly_trends = monthly_trends.sort_values(by=['year_added','month_added'])
In [61]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
sns.lineplot(data=monthly_trends, x='month_added', y='count', hue='year_added', palette= 'tab20', marker = '')

plt.title("Monthly Trends in Netflix Content Additions Over Years")
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel('Number of titles added')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title='Year', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05,1), loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Key Takeaways -

Netflix significantly ramped up its content between 20172019

Movies dominate over TV shows

US and India are key content contributors

Genre diversity is high, with some surprises like "Independent Movies"

Ratings like TV-MA dominate, hinting at mature content focus
